  "summary": "Before his death, Aristide Leonidas secretly replaced his will with a different version during a signing ceremony witnessed by two servants to avoid suspicion. In this document, he expressed gratitude for his family's loyalty and requested that Sophia protect them. Following his death, Mr. Gasteyer of the law firm Carlum and Gasteyer & Co. expressed offense at Aristide's perceived lack of trust, leading to a confrontation with Charles's father. Inspector Taverna noted that Aristide was a cunning man who had avoided using Gasteyer's firm for suspicious business dealings.\n\nThe investigation takes a violent turn when Charles receives an urgent call from his girlfriend, who reports that Josephine has been severely injured by a blow to the head and may not recover. Charles, his father, and Taverna travel to Swinley, where Sophia informs them that Josephine has been taken to General de Macte Barcin Hospital.\n\nUpon arriving at the property, Sophia leads the men to a dilapidated courtyard containing a laundry room. A marble lion doorstop, originally from the front door, had been placed on top of the laundry room door as a trap. Sophia explains that Josephine had a habit of swaying on the door's bottom groove. Taverna observes that the trap was likely set to fall, though it was imprecise. While Taverna notes the killer was careful, Charles discovers dirt fragments on an old wooden chair, suggesting someone with muddy shoes stood on it to set the trap. Sophia reports finding Josephine unconscious with blood on her hair at 1:15 PM. Taverna concludes the doorstop must have been placed between breakfast and 1:00 PM.",
